Anything I set into `Decal.transformationOffset` is somehow reduced so it behaves like vector `(0, 0)`.

To invalidate it (internally: `updated=false`) I do this:

``` java
decal.setX(decal.getX());
```

`Decal#transformVertices()` has this code:

``` java
float tx, ty;
if (transformationOffset != null) {
    tx = -transformationOffset.x;
    ty = -transformationOffset.y;
} else {
    tx = ty = 0;
}
```

Debugger breakpoints enter properly, so `tx` and `ty` is definetely not zero but values set through `transformationOffset`.

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/31058/10111840/1f4cb940-63d7-11e5-892f-b5cdacfc73e0.png)

Class CumulativeDistribution returned wrong values. Can be easily checked with the next code:

``` java
CumulativeDistribution<Integer> cdf = new CumulativeDistribution<Integer>();
cdf.add(1, 1);
cdf.add(2, 1);
cdf.add(3, 1);
cdf.generateNormalized();
int one = 0, two = 0, three = 0;
for (int i = 0; i < 100000; i++) {
    int v = cdf.value();
    if (v == 1) one++;
    else if (v == 2) two++;
    else if (v == 3) three++;
}
System.out.println("1: " + one + " 2: " + two + " 3: " + three);
```

Prints before fix:
1: 66714 2: 0 3: 33286
After fix:
1: 33383 2: 33489 3: 33128

when create a framebuffer object with stencil and depth buffer on android, the glCheckFramebufferStatus return GL_FRAMEBUFFER_UNSUPPORTED

actually on android, if both stencil and depth buffer will be used in framebuffer object, the renderbuffer should use stencil and depth combined renderbuffer,  such as GLES11EXT.GL_DEPTH24_STENCIL8_OES. Here is my code specific to android platform

if (hasStencil && hasDepth) {
            gl.glBindRenderbuffer(GL20.GL_RENDERBUFFER, depthStencilBufferHandle);
            gl.glRenderbufferStorage(GL20.GL_RENDERBUFFER, GLES11Ext.GL_DEPTH24_STENCIL8_OES, colorTexture.getWidth(), colorTexture.getHeight());
            gl.glFramebufferRenderbuffer(GL20.GL_FRAMEBUFFER, GL20.GL_DEPTH_ATTACHMENT, GL20.GL_RENDERBUFFER, depthStencilBufferHandle);
            gl.glFramebufferRenderbuffer(GL20.GL_FRAMEBUFFER, GL20.GL_STENCIL_ATTACHMENT, GL20.GL_RENDERBUFFER, depthStencilBufferHandle);
        }

If you create a cursor with a height and width of 32 and set the hotspot coords to 31 lwjgl will crash.
It crashs because we subtract 4 in https://github.com/libgdx/libgdx/blob/master/backends/gdx-backend-lwjgl/src/com/badlogic/gdx/backends/lwjgl/LwjglCursor.java#L83 for no real reason.
Changing 

```
lwjglCursor = new org.lwjgl.input.Cursor(pixmap.getWidth(), pixmap.getHeight(), xHotspot, pixmap.getHeight() - yHotspot
                - 4, 1, IntBuffer.wrap(pixelsARGBflipped), null);
```

to

```
lwjglCursor = new org.lwjgl.input.Cursor(pixmap.getWidth(), pixmap.getHeight(), xHotspot, pixmap.getHeight() - yHotspot
                - 1, 1, IntBuffer.wrap(pixelsARGBflipped), null);
```

should fix it.

